\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chromosome Conformation Capture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chromosome Conformation Capture (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "3C"
description "Chromosome Conformation Capture"

\end_inset

3C) is a ligation based proximity assay.
 First published in 2002 by Dekker 
\emph on
et.
 al.

\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dekker2002b"

\end_inset

 it allows the physical association of sequences of DNA to be interrogated.
 3C has become a key methodology in the field of nuclear organisation, and
 a number of new techniques use it as a base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3C works by fixing protein and DNA in place with formaldehyde.
 A restriction enyme is used to cut the DNA, typically recognising a 6 base
 pair sequence, so cutting on average once every 1.2 Kb (
\begin_inset Formula $6^{4}=1296$
\end_inset

).
 This results in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hairballs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of cross linked DNA and protein which are diluted into a large volume.
 A ligation reaction is then run, which favours ligations between sequences
 held together by the formaldehyde cross links.
 Cross links are reversed and the DNA is purified, leaving a 3C 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

library
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Within this library, the frequency with which restriction fragments are
 found ligated together corresponds to their degree of interaction within
 the nucleus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 3C library is a basis for a number of different assays that all measure
 interaction frequencies.
 Traditional 3C uses PCR with primers positioned adjacent to the restriction
 enzyme recognition sites of two loci of interest.
 If a PCR product is detected, these two sequences were physically close
 within the nucleus.
 The strength of bands on a gel can be used to quantify the strength of
 this interaction, and qPCR can be used to accurately assess this for a
 large number of primer pairs (3C qPCR).
 Both of these techniques are used to probe interactions on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one-to-one
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 basis; that is, investigating the interaction between two specific loci
 at a time.
\end_layout

