 Further work on this step showed that the SDS treatment and subsequent
 Triton-X100 quenching of the SDS were having a dramatic effect on the digestion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I ran a concentration gradient of Triton-X100 with a digestion using purified
 plasmid DNA which showed residual SDS inhibiting the reaction when there
 was insufficient Triton-X100 to quench all of the SDS (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Restriction-Enzyme-Tests"

\end_inset

A).
 The concentration of Triton-X100 had a similar effect on the digestion
 efficiency of BamHi with cross linked chromatin (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Restriction-Enzyme-Tests"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I followed these tests with an experiment using a panel of different restriction
 enzymes, some of which are commonly used in 3C based techniques.
 I used cells which were fixed with the normal 2% formaldehyde and a weaker
 1% formaldehyde fix, and I ran the digestion step with and without the
 initial SDS disruption and Triton-X100 quenching (Fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Restriction-Enzyme-Tests"

\end_inset

).
 These digestions clearly showed that BamHI was far less efficient at digesting
 cross linked chromatin than the other restriction enzymes in every condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point, instead of continuing to try to optimise the 3C to work with
 BamHI, I went back to the drawing board and looked at which other enzymes
 could be suitable.
 The restriction enzyme AseI had good performance under all of the conditions,
 and gave suitable fragment sizes in and around the break point cluster
 regions of both 
\emph on
BCR
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
.
 Further digestion efficiency qPCR tests showed it's efficiency at a far
 superior 81 - 99% of sites being cut
